<br>
You, my friend, are exactly right.  It strikes me odd that only now after PoP has been out so long that Sony is finally recognizing there is melee issues between warriors / knights.  I think your absolutely right in the point that this is simply a beta test for EQ2.. I think Sony has finally realized they have a real problem and some players won't migrate to EQ2 where the melee situation will just be the same with just more toonish eye candy to behold.<br>
<br>
With that said, and coming from the enchanter standpoint - unless the warrior is from a reputable guild - I usually /sigh when the group leader says a warrior is coming to tank.  Does this mean I won't take warriors, not at all.<br>
<br>
I've heard some good ideas, I think perhaps a mix of some ideas could yield the best fix though.  I've been thinking this...<br>
<br>
- Increase warrior mitigation noticeably and decrease knight mitigation noticeably.  Perhaps (?) +10% to warriors, -10% to knights.<br>
<br>
- Give the warrior some utility to bring to groups, but with reduced effectiveness.  These could be limited by reuse times or perhaps create an action bar to act like mana for the pure melee classes. For example...<br>
--knee bash (short duration (6 sec) snare with maybe a reuse of 3 minutes)<br>
--headbutt (casting interrupt and perhaps a mana DD.. detrimental effect could be warrior taking damage on a critical failure, use the reuse time for balance)<br>
--charge (short duration boost to the groups ATK that doesn't take a buff slot, maybe a 5 minute reuse)<br>
<br>
- How about giving the warrior a slight chance to stun (1 sec) with each strike.  I'm talking a slight chance, and the stun could be agro generating.  This could reflect the warriors supreme battle prowless and offset pallies with stun, making warriors have an edge in battle against casters.<br>
<br>
I don't have the answer, don't claim too.. but I do know something needs to be done.  I think the larger problem is not with the classes as they are, but with the combat engine in general.  With each expansion, equipment has more stats, more stats, more stats, more hp, more mana, more hp, more mana.. etc, etc and etc.<br>
<br>
Some of these problems, at least as I see them, would not even exist if the combat system was more focused on <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>the toon's combat skills</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> rather than the stats on his / her equipment.  Ah well, that's awhole different thread in itself.<br>
